##Fight plague, caricature, chase after a star, clap Vlog... This 90 hind nurse is another kind again strong

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

By Keith Chen, _ thepaper_news _

Post-90s nurses from Ruijin Hospital made anti-epidemic Vlog on the front line. Video Source: Interviewee, Video Clip: Zeng Yiwen 01:34

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Xia Qionghua, who loves watching TV and watching TV, held several positions at the Wuhan anti-epidemic Front, including sorting out the garbage in the isolation ward and the clothes the patients took off.

He worked for more than 10 hours at the intensive-care unit, feeding them with water, feeding them with food and cleaning their urine and feces in addition to nursing them.

Shen Yan, who had written "Jeremy Lin's girlfriend" on her protective clothing, emerged from the isolation ward covered in sweat and her face was covered with deep marks from a mask.

They are the nurses of the Post 90s generation in Shanghai. They teach patients how to play video software. They relieve pressure by drawing comics, watching TV, singing. They write all kinds of words or even draw pictures on their protective clothing, but they are strong in the fight against the plague.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhu Youqi sent his cartoon to the patient who was about to be discharged from hospital.

Post-1990s "soul painter" creates "hot and dry noodles meet Xiaolongbao"

Cartooning is a skill that many post-90s nurses can easily master.

"Hot dry noodles don't be afraid, Xiaolongbao" , "come on! We are all Wuhan People" , this is born in 1993 Zhu Youqi's cartoon works on the text.

She is from the North Hospital of Shanghai Ruijin Hospital and currently works in the E3-4 isolation ward of Wuhan Tongji Guanggu Hospital. According to the schedule, it takes her four hours to enter the isolation ward every time. It takes her half an hour to wear a protective suit before entering the ward. After entering the ward, she can not drink water or go to the toilet, after entering the cabin patrol ward a circle or medicine, rice, treatment, and so on, in the middle to slow down, or there will be some lack of oxygen feeling.

The first time she was ready to leave the cabin, she recalled, she took off her suit and bent over. Water dripped down her goggles. She found that it was sweat dripping down her goggles.

Her painting hobby brought her skills to the front lines, where her work was pasted on the windows of her ward and she would draw pictures to give to patients who were about to leave the hospital.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Cartoon works by Zou Fangcao, a post-90s nurse from Shanghai First People's Hospital. This article, except for the signature, is for the interviewees

"The Xiaolongbao meets the hot-dry surface, and a river ties two cities together. " In recent days, an original cartoon depicting a smooth "meeting" between Shanghai Xiaolongbao and Wuhan's hot-dry surface has been screened in the circle of Friends of the front-line medical team of the Shanghai First People's Hospital, "For serial" and "for the update" of the demand to come.

The original author is from the First People's Hospital in Shanghai after 90 nurse Zou Fangcao, she is "invisible" in the medical team's "soul painting hand. The night before she arrived in Wuhan, she packed a suitcase -- a drawing tool called a tablet computer.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Q version medical team members drawn by Zou Fangcao, a post-90s nurse.

On the first night of her arrival at the Thunder Mountain in Wuhan on February 19, she drew a white coat version and a camouflage coat version of a "military photo" of a nurse and a doctor's brother. Unexpectedly, from that night on, things got out of hand, many of her colleagues urged her to write.

Gradually, the daily update of the "illustrated edition" diary, has become a daily work Zou Fangcao after the end of the well-being of torture.

"The white everywhere in the isolation ward and the dense written records of cases on the record books, I hope that through the outline of lines, color changes can record every scene in the thor mountain ward vivid, but also give my city a 'comrades-in-arms' a change of mood, ease the mood, " Zou Fangcao said.

In her view, over time, the photo will become a mobile phone album of a string of data, only draw down, can be remembered, become eternal.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"PAC man" , a favorite cartoon of post-90s nurse Zou Fangcao.

Before each painting, she would relive one of the most memorable events or scenes of the day. Daily nagging but meticulous care of their lives, "team mom" , "Team Dad" , wearing a full set of equipment to remember a hundred times to note, become Ultraman and virus battle colleague "Baymax" , the first "balint group" of a city medical team in the station... the once serious and boring details of daily work, in her pen into a "heart painting.

Her favorite painting was pac-man, which she thought looked like the medical team, "To eat Tsutsu is to cure the sick, and to eat Tsutsu is to try to avoid the little monster, just as we struggle every day without touching the virus, and recovery is our greatest victory. "

Downloading short videos for patients to distract them

A small protective clothing, also became the 90 nurses "creative place. ".

Do not write their name, also do not write from which hospital, creative 90 some people wrote "hot dry surface refuels" , still others wrote their idols.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Post-90s nurse Shen Yan wrote "Jeremy Lin's girlfriend" on her protective suit.

Shen Yan, a post-90s nurse, is one of the first group to support the Hubei Medical Team in Shanghai. She is currently working in Jinyintan hospital.

Despite the harsh conditions, heavy shifts and the risk of infection, Shen was optimistic, writing "Jeremy Lin's girlfriend" on her protective clothing to cheer her up.

On Feb. 19, she returned home from her night shift at 8 p.m. , posted a message praying for "an early end to the epidemic, " and said she also wanted to go to Shougang to watch Jeremy Lin play. The next day, she saw Jeremy Lin retweeting her account and excitedly told her friend, "I feel so dizzy that my back doesn't hurt and my legs don't hurt anymore. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Take off the protective clothing out of the isolation ward Shen Yan is all sweaty.

Born in 1990, Zhang Junjie, a male nurse from the Catheterization Department of Shanghai Chest Hospital, worked at Jinyintan hospital for over a month. He wrote a big "Wu Tsing-Fong fan" on the back of his suit, with the words "willing Comancheria to walk it" and "turn youth into her" on both sides, those are the words from the song the wind rises, Sung by singer Wu Tsing-Fong.

He worked for more than 10 hours at the intensive-care unit, wearing a heavy, stuffy suit. Because there are no nurses, each nurse has to do a lot of work outside of basic care, feeding, feeding, cleaning, even combing hair and cutting nails.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhang Junjie, a post-1990s male nurse from the Catheterization Department of Shanghai Chest Hospital, wrote "Wu Tsing-Fong Fan" behind her protective clothing, along with a couple of lyrics. WECHAT public accounts@chatterbox

Zhang also helped a patient download a short video at his bedside. "It was like he had discovered a new continent, and he found the software was quite easy to use and fun, which distracted him. " Zhang said the patient's genuine happiness was a driving force in his work.

Watching TV and eating TV to decompress

"stress is nothing, nothing that can't be solved with one meal, one bad meal, two meals, nothing that can't be dealt with, " said Xia Qionghua, a nurse born in the 1990s.

Xia Qionghua is a nurse in the Department of hepatobiliary surgery of Ruijin Hospital. For her, compared to working in Shanghai, the pace of work in Wuhan Tongji Guanggu Hospital district is even more intense. She can be said to be doing several jobs, sorting out doctor's orders every day, helping patients coordinate various examinations and tests, and sometimes doing hospital-sense work, sterilize the inside and outside of the cabin.

"although my work is trivial, it's actually very important. I feel more responsible than before. Our work is mainly to build a bridge between the inside and outside of the isolation ward. It's for the continuity of patient care. After seeing the orders of the patient's laboratory doctor, especially the orders of nucleic acid test and CT test, we will inform the nurses in the cabin, help the patient to make an appointment for examination, and every day before leaving work, we will also check on the implementation of these examinations, and then do the handover work, " Xia Qionghua said.

Her work also includes sorting out the garbage in the isolation ward, working clothes taken off by medical staff, scrubs and even clothes taken off by patients. Every day before work, she also have to go to get living materials and protective materials, who are missing to take care of her, colleagues are affectionately called her "summer aunt. ".

Born in 1992, one of her hobbies is food. Chatting or eating with her family and friends is one of her ways to relieve stress. She also watches food broadcasts at hotels during breaks, "The thought of having Dad Cook all that food for me when I get back will make me feel better. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A photo of Xia Qionghua as she prepares for her trip to Wuhan.

Xia Qionghua also has another hobby to sing, when the rest will hum two lines in the hotel, also has produced an anti-plague Vlog, Vlog's music "mutually love" or his own singing. "I was inspired by the people around me, " she says of the project

"My friends in Group A, including the team in Ruijin, all make me feel like family, " she said. "When we get tired from work, our friends donate things and share them in our 'mini-mart' . Our Group leader, Zhu Lin, is just as warm to us as her mother. When one of the kids gets sick, she immediately adjusts the schedule, brings Three Meals a Day to the kids and performs dangerous operations. She always goes ahead on her own. When we get tired from work, the other kids in the group tell us jokes and share them with us, and the patients praise us, which makes us feel like family. "

Xia Qionghua has been hard to forget the words the patient said to himself: "can't see your faces, but your eyes are particularly bright. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Zhu Youqi (center) poses with colleagues in the isolation ward of Tongji Guanggu Hospital in Wuhan.

Similarly, Zhu Youqi has heard, "although I can't see your face clearly, thank you for helping me. " Every time she hears this sentence, she feels that she is doing a very meaningful thing.

Zhu Youqi said frankly: "In the past, everyone was under the impression that the post-90s generation were spoiled and could not afford hardship. However, nearly half of the people in our medical team were post-90s. As a post-90s member, I was also an active member of the party when the epidemic occurred. The post-90s generation can take actions to prove that they are able to shoulder their responsibilities, defend their motherland, and use what they have learned to prevent the spread of the epidemic. "

"My grandfather is an old party member. I have wanted to follow his example since I was a child. My family supports my decision and thinks I should contribute to the epidemic, " said Xia Qionghua, a nurse born in the 1990s.
